Perhaps a fisheye lens is too much for a birdhouse.
You never learn from experience.
I could have known better, since I already built one with a "normal" lens before.
I will write more about it over the weekend once I have installed the second one.
Let's just say the birds will have a better internet connection than I did in 2015.
At least that's the plan.
The box that already has a nest is using up a lot of WLAN data.
With the other one, it's a bit more difficult for it to go online.
Okay, I hung up the new nest box today. This is how it looks at its new spot in the garden.
But let's go back a bit. No one is asking: "What exactly is inside?"
On top is one of these ESP32 camera boards with a camera featuring a fisheye lens and an IR LED, which I got from a Raspberry Pi camera.
The reason for the strange shape of this plastic box is the swiveling side panel of the birdhouse. I bought it like that and couldn't change it, so I had to build around it.
Since there is no electricity in the garden, the whole thing is powered by a solar panel and a 2600 mAh 18650 cell.
I didn't photograph the cell or the charger, but here is a picture of the panel.
The battery is in the gray box attached to the side of the birdhouse.
If it's charged, I get about 4 hours of runtime.
That's a feature, I'd say. So the birds also get some privacy.
At first, I wasn't sure if the internet in our garden would be sufficient for this setup. The old access points I replaced last fall wouldn't have been enough.
But the new ones cover this area very well.
It's almost a shame, because I had planned to install a TP-Link cpe210 on the roof and aim it downward into the garden.
Maybe I'll do that if/when I set up more birdhouses with cameras. I probably need that in areas that are further away from the house.
Now the camera is offline, and I don't know why. It turned off only an hour after sunset.
Perhaps the battery didn't charge anymore three hours before sunset because there wasn't enough light.
Or maybe less than half a day was not enough to fully charge the battery.
I probably have to wait and see what happens tomorrow.
I don't have telemetry for the battery. I might have to change that in the future.
In general, a few more sensors would be a good thing, I think.
And maybe a battery that at least theoretically is able to keep the thing running all night.
Oh yeah, and another lens.
Fisheye is pretty overkill.
But I'm already looking for parts on Digikey so that I can build my own board specifically for that.
Or maybe not. We'll see.
And he is still offline.
Great.
According to the actual solar cells on the house, we only have about 90 minutes of proper sunlight.
Let's wait another hour or two to see what happens – or maybe not.
Still offline.
It's never easy.
It turned out that in the USB-C breakout board I used to connect the charger, the 5V and GND were swapped on the silkscreen.
I swapped the cables and now the charging indicator is lit.
The ESP didn't come online immediately. Let's wait a few minutes.
An hour has passed and it's still offline.
It looks like it's restarting and triggering a Tasmota reset function.
I think the panel is just useless. I've now ordered a larger one and hope that will work.
Look what I found in my workshop.
A 24-V panel. Unfortunately, the sun is already so low (and partly blocked by a tree) that the value drops practically to zero as soon as I turn on the device.
I'll probably have to wait until tomorrow to see if it's sufficient for this setup or if I need the better panel I ordered.
According to Amazon, I bought the panel in 2021 and it is supposed to deliver 12 V at a maximum of 1.2 A.
So either something is wrong with the panel or my multimeter, or the data has changed.
Good news!
You changed the data and the ones I have are wrong.
The old one and also the new listing title call it a 12 V 10-W panel.
